msgid "Forward Proxy"
msgstr ""

# c4867d3eca9b46e392a735ead1191455
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:23
msgid ""
"The Apache Traffic Server is a general purpose proxy, configurable as "
"both a reverse and forward proxy."
msgstr ""

# 586931c4051a43b08f4b115d4a14d57e
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:26
msgid ""
"A forward proxy can be used as a central tool in your infrastructure to "
"access the web and it may be combined with a cache to lower your overall "
"bandwidth usage. Forward proxies act as a gatekeeper between client "
"browsers on your local network and all (or some, at your configuration's "
"discretion) web sites accessed by those clients. The forward proxy will "
"receive the HTTP requests, perform any filtering or request alteration "
"rules you establish, and when appropriate forward the request on to its "
"destination website. The response will return through your proxy, where "
"it may optionally be cached and/or modified, and then returned to the "
"original client."
msgstr ""

# b9f1c5ccba3046a1a48e5ea6d63fa3dd
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:36
msgid "There are two modes in which your forward proxy may operate:"
msgstr ""

# 52ed01e11746483b81cbd8224d671a3c
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:39
msgid ""
"Each client must be configured explicitly to use the forward proxy. "
"Client browsers will be aware of the fact they are using a proxy and will"
" form their HTTP requests appropriately. This results in the initial HTTP"
" command being issued with fully qualified URIs that contain the "
"destination hostname::"
msgstr ""

# 08503ce09de44dc886c87e721d160d62
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:56
msgid "Transparent Proxy"
msgstr ""

# 51090390661245bca880e381a1125255
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:47
msgid ""
"The use of a transparent proxy is typically done in concert with network "
"routing rules which redirect all outbound HTTP traffic through your "
"proxy. Clients will behave, and form their HTTP requests, as if they are "
"contacting the remote site directly, and will not be aware of the "
"existence of a proxy server in between themselves and the remote servers."
" HTTP requests will be generated per their usual form, with only paths in"
" the command and a separate Host request header::"
msgstr ""

# 0a1ce8fe616f44c98b75b0b7d30717f9
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:58
msgid ""
"Apache Traffic Server may be configured to operate as both a forward and "
"a transparent proxy simultaneously."
msgstr ""

# 8283e137e28a4e4da502f68bd2679ae7
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:62
msgid "Proxy Configuration"
msgstr ""

# f525eb53c24845159a1c620ff2b16c98
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:64
msgid ""
"Configuring basic forward proxy operation in Traffic Server is quite "
"simple and straightforward."
msgstr ""

# 0e596a4fb2b249dc94819bdfcfb1d1e4
#: ../../admin-guide/configuration/transparent-forward-proxying.en.rst:67
msgid ""
"Permit Traffic Server to process requests for hosts not explicitly "
"configured in the remap rules, by modifying "
":ts:cv:`proxy.config.url_remap.remap_required` in "
":file:`records.config`::"
msgstr ""

# 3fd42dba3556442bbdb5cb6d5b00c0b6
